(2,'Q2. Quelle commande permet de créer une connexion entre un déôt local et un dépôt distant ?',0,'git remote add new',1,'git remote add origin',0,'git remote new origin',0,'git remote origin\n\n[Reference](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/20291731/how-to-connect-to-a-remote-git-repository)'),
(3,'Q3. Décrivez ce que font ces commandes sur l\'historique de vos commits:\n\n```bash\ngit reset --hard HEAD~5\ngit merge --squash HEAD@{1}\n```\n',0,'They reset the HEAD to the fifth commit in the repo, then merge to the master branch.',1,'The current branch\'s HEAD is reset back five commits, then prior commits are squashed into a single commit.',0,'They delete the last five commits.',0,'They merge the last five commits into a new branch.\n\n**Explanation:**\n\n- `git reset --hard HEAD~5` resets the current branch to the commit just before the last 5 (see `man gitrevisions` for details about this notation and other cool alternatives like `HEAD@{2 days ago}`). As it is a hard reset, it will also overwrite every change in the working tree as well. See `man git-reset`.\n- `git merge --squash HEAD@{1}` HEAD@{1} is where the branch was just before the previous command (again, see `man gitrevisions`). This command sets the state of the index to be as it would just after a merge from that commit. This whole operation could be a way to take 5 commits from a branch in which you started a new feature and squash them to a single commit, a meaningful one.'),
(4,'Q4. Your current project has several branches; master, beta, and push-notifications. You\'ve just finished the notification feature in the push-notification branch, and you want to commit it to beta branch. How can you accomplish this?',0,'Checkout the push-notifications branch and run git merge beta',0,'Checkout the master branch and run git merge beta -> push-notification',0,'Delete the push-notification branch and it will be committed to the master branch automatically',1,'Checkout the beta branch and run git merge push-notification'),
(5,'Q5. Which of the following is 1 you when you use the following command?\n\n`git add -A`\n',1,'All new and updated files are staged',0,'Files are staged in alphabetical order.',0,'All new files are staged',0,'Only updated files are staged'),
(6,'Q6. What will the following command print to the Terminal?\n\n`git remote -v`\n',1,'A list of remote repositories and their URLs',0,'The current git version you\'re running',0,'An inline editor for modifying remote repositories',0,'The last 5 git versions you\'ve installed'),
(7,'Q8. What does the following command do to the git repository?\n\n`git reset --soft HEAD^`\n',0,'It deletes all previous commits and reset the repository history back to its initial state.',0,'It resets the working branch to the first commit.',0,'It keeps the HEAD at the current commit, but clears all previous commits.',1,'It sets HEAD to the previous commit and leaves changes from the undone commit in the stage/index.'),
(8,'Q9. You find a bug in your project, but can\'t locate where it was introduced in the commit history. How would you diagnose this problem?',0,'Manually backtrack through your commit history.',0,'Use git search -diff to compare all commits in your repository history.',0,'Run a git rebase to find the buggy commit.',1,'Use git bisect to compare the buggy commit to an early commit that works as expected.'),
(9,'Q10. Why would the following command be used?\n\n`git rebase -i HEAD~10`\n',0,'To run a comparative search of the last 10 commits for differences',1,'To list the last 10 commits and modify them with either the squash or fixup command',0,'To delete the last 10 commits and reset the HEAD',0,'In order to locally cache the last 10 commits'),
(10,'Q11. Why would you use a pre-receive hook in your remote repository?',0,'You wouldn\'t, you would use it in the local repository',1,'To execute a script when a remote receives a push that is triggered before any refs are updated',0,'To fire a script after updates are made to the remote repository',0,'To debug all commit tags and release versions'),
