(14,'Q15. How can you display a list of files added or modified in a specific commit?',0,'Find the commit in the remote repository, as that\'s the only place that kind of information is stored.',1,'Use the `diff-tree` command with the commit hash.',0,'Run `git commit --info` with the commit hash.',0,'Access the commit stash data with `git stash`.'),
(15,'Q16. What files is this .gitignore programmed to leave out?\n\n```shell\n#.swift\nbuild/\n\n*.txt\n*.metadata\n```\n',0,'All files with a .swift, .txt, or metadata file extension, as well as the entire build directory',0,'Only the build directory',1,'All files in the build directory, as well as files ending with .txt or .metadata',0,'Only files with .swift and .txt extensions.\n\nA line starting with `#` serves as a comment. Hence `# .swift` does not do anything. See `man gitignore`.'),
(16,'Q17. After you make changes to a local repository, you run the following command. What will this do?\n\n`git commit -a -m \"Refactor code base\"`\n',0,'Nothing, you can\'t use multiple options in the same command',0,'Adds all new files to the staging area',0,'Commits all new files with a message',1,'Adds all modified files to the staging area, then commits them with a message'),
(17,'Q18. After checking your git status you get the following output, which shows the file beta-notes.js in the commit but also unstaged. How can this situation occur?\n\n```shell\nChange to be committed:\n\n(use \'git reset HEAD <file>...\' to unstage)\nmodified: beta-notes.js\nChanges not staged for commit:\n(use \'git add <file>...\' to update what will be committed)\n(use \'git checkout --<file>...\' to discard changes in working directory)\n\nmodified: beta-notes.js\n```\n',0,'There were two copies of beta-notes.js but one was deleted',1,'beta-notes.js was staged, then modified afterwards, creating two different versions of the file',0,'Two copies of beta-notes.js were created, but only one is being tracked',0,'There are two tracked copies of beta-notes.js, but one was removed from the commit'),
(18,'Q19. Where are files stored before they are committed to the local repository?',0,'Saved files',0,'git documents',1,'Staging area',0,'git cache'),
(19,'Q20. What commands would you use to force an overwrite of your local files with the master branch?',0,'⠀\n  ```bash\n  git pull --all\n  git reset --hard origin/master\n  ```',0,'⠀\n  ```bash\n  git pull -u origin master\n  git reset --hard master\n  ```',0,'⠀\n  ```bash\n  git pull origin master\n  git reset --hard origin/myCurrentBranch\n  ```',1,'⠀\n\n  ```bash\n  git fetch --all\n  git reset --hard origin/master\n  ```\n\n- The command `pull` is `fetch` followed by either `merge` or `rebase` (in this case, `merge`). We don\'t want to merge. Merge would be an action to our **repository**. We just want to overwrite our **local files**.'),
(20,'Q21. Which statement is 1 when you use the git add -A command?',0,'Only new files in the working directory are staged to the index.',1,'All new and updated files from the working directory are staged to the index.',0,'All files in the working directory are staged to the index in alphabetical order.',0,'Only updated files in the working directory are staged to the index.'),
